Description: The initial work on CostDataOnLine.com started in early 2006 and at that time, was driven by a demand from the Cost Engineering Industry.
Full Description: The initial work on CostDataOnLine.com started in early 2006 and at that time, was driven by a demand from the Cost Engineering Industry.  After months of work establishing comprehensive labor data, they began to see the need for and the future of CostDataOnLine.com. Today they are the new home for the Richardson Construction Estimating Standards.  CostDataOnLine.com will be the vehicle that brings the Richardson Construction Estimating Standards into the 21st Century.  Their goal is to provide you the user, with a complete comprehensive view of the city in which the work is to be preformed.  They present data that relates to weather, transportation and location as well as labor rates and cost standards that are based upon the city.     There has always been a higher level of detail within the Richardson Construction Estimating Standards. Their priority is to enhance this detail, by delivering Richardson Dynamic Data via the web to your desktop. Richardson Dynamic Data is data that reflects local labor rates, up to date material prices and man-hours with over 45 years of history and refinement.   The team at CostDataOnLine.com is made-up of experienced costing professionals with decades of costing and creation experience with the Richardson Construction Estimating Standards.  Their team has completed the majority of the work on the Location, Labor, Transportation and Weather areas within CostDataOnLine.com.  They have begun to incorporate the Richardson Construction Estimating Standards into The CostDataOnLine.com format.  Beginning with Pipe and continuing with Electrical, Instrumentation and Equipment etc…  It will be some time untill they completed the transition process for all 512 accounts.  Registered users will have immediate access to Richardson Dynamic Data, as it is updated and converted.  Richardson Dynamic Data will be available as each section is completed.  In the interim for incomplete areas, registered users will be provided access to the latest version of the Richardson Construction Estimating Standards.     Their team is not only made up of internal associates, it also includes hundreds of manufacturers, software providers such as Aspen Technology, Inc. and the ultimate data source, you the end users.

Description: The first female friendly dating app. Women ask questions and eliminate guys based on how they respond.
Headquarters Regions: San Francisco Bay Area, West Coast, Western US
Full Description: The first female-friendly dating app that empowers women and eliminates the most basic problems with apps like Tinder. Women ask questions and single out guys based on how they respond. Men cannot message women until women give permission. Customer Pain 1. Women being inundated with offensive messages on dating apps. 2. Women and men are overloaded with connections. Less than 10% message each other and less than 1% meet in real life. 3. Women and men have no context and therefore do not have anything to talk about when matching. Their Solution By putting women in the driver’s seat we create a better experience for everyone. When men feel as if they have been hand-picked they are more inclined to take the interaction seriously and less inclined to send offensive messages. Target Market They target college and graduate students between the ages of 18-26.The total college and graduate student market is about 24 million, and the twenty-something crowd exceeds 50 million people. Revenue Model They use in-app currency called Golden Tickets to allow users to make internal purchases.With GoldenTickets women can (a) increase their visibility (b) refine their matches, and (c) customize their profile and questions. Men can use Golden Tickets to (a) explain their answers and (b) give virtual gifts to women. They also accrue revenue through banner advertising. Go-to-Market Their “top-down” approach uses major social media to target users by age, location, gender, and university. Their “bottom-up” approach creates stickiness on college campuses by having foot traffic. They launched on a single college campus and within 10 days they were able to get 2,000 users (at 1/10th the cost of industry standard). Their users have posted and responded over 22,000 times within that 10 day period. Management Team The entire team has previously worked together in the same space on SetMeUp, which connected users to new people through mutual friends. At SetMeUp, they raised a 500k seed round to scale to 30,000+ users and 68 million profiles. They brought on the early-stage founder of Match.com. They recently closed down the app to refocus their efforts on the Singled Out app, since this is more responsive to the current problems women face in today’s dating market.
Industry Groups: Apps, Internet Services, Media and Entertainment, Software
